Question: How do I access SciFinder?
Answer: SciFinder access requires TWO activated accounts: an SJSU email account and an account with SciFinder itself.      To obtain an account for SciFinder, you need to do the following:    1) have an email account with a suffix of @students.sjsu.edu (go to http://uts.sjsu.edu/systems/campus-email/student-email/ to get set up with your account if you haven't already activated it)    2) log in http://library.sjsu.edu/electronic-journals-index/get-library-passwords to obtain the registration URL for SciFinder     3) after logging in, find and click on the registration URL for SciFinder and then register with SciFinder using your @students.sjsu.edu account (SciFinder will send you an email with a link to activate your account)    4) log into your @students.sjsu.edu account and click on the activation link    5) log into SciFinder (http://library.calstate.edu/sanjose/databases/proxy/CAL07371) and you're all set!    Steps 1-4 are only required when registering and activating your account, so they're one-time only.  After you've completed this process, you will only need to complete Step 5 with your unique username and password to access SciFinder.

What should I do in this case?
Answer: 1) Create a back-up of your document RRP2p2 by using the "Save As" feature in Word or right-click the file icon and copy the file in Windows Explorer  2) Open the back-up and select Convert  3) Check to make sure that your document looks fine.      Once you choose to save the document, you cannot undo the conversion.  This should bring your document to the most current Write 'n Cite version.  If there are any errors, you will still have your original file.

Question: pHion Berry Superfruit
Answer: You're researching pHion Berry Superfruit.  It is seldom that you'd find a peer-reviewed article examining the effectiveness and efficacy of a commercial product.      To complete your assignment, I would suggest the following:    1) Identify the ingredients of your consumer product (which you have already done)  2) Choose a couple of the ingredients and study the effects of these items in the scientific literature (go to the library website and search in CINAHL. Academic Search Premier, PubMed, ScienceDirect)  3) In the online pHion Berry Superfruit ad (http://www.phionbalance.com/ph-balancing-products/antioxidants/phion-berry-superfruit/), there are some citations for the various antioxidant ingredients  4) You could explore some of those citations or search for related articles about the role(s) that these antioxidants may play or conduct searches with some of these possible keywords: [ingredient], efficacy, antioxidant, supplement, etc.  5) Based on the results, refine your searches to find articles that may be of interest.    You're not going to find articles about this product, but you can find articles about the active ingredients in pHion Berry Superfruit.
